<DOC><DOCNO> AP890711-0160 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1930EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-11 0551</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0576</SECOND><HEAD>Four Killed in Guerrilla Rocket Attacks</HEAD><BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Moslem guerrillas bombarded the capitalwith rockets Tuesday, killing four people shortly after theSoviet-backed government announced a unilateral cease-fire to mark aMoslem holiday.   After the attack, Afghan Foreign Ministry spokesman, MohammadNabi Amani warned of growing public anger against Pakistan for itssupport of the guerrillas and warned that Afghanistan would strikeback.   Meanwhile, hundreds of Afghans marched through Kabul urging thegovernment to take military action against Pakistan, where most ofthe insurgents are based.   The Moslem guerrillas, supported by the United States, havefought an 11-year war against the Soviet-backed government.   On Tuesday, at least six rockets slammed into Kabul after a weekof intensified guerrilla attacks on the capital.   On Monday, at least 55 rockets hit the city of 2.25 millionpeople, killing 18 civilians and two soldiers and wounding 51people, the government said. Hospital sources said that at least 165people, including 22 children, were hurt in the bombing, which alsodestroyed a weapons depot near the airport.   But in a statement issued by the government-in-exile inIslamabad, the guerrillas denied firing rockets at civilian targets.   ``Mujahedeen commanders around Kabul and other cities have strictinstructions to aim only at the enemy's military installations andto be careful not to miss their targets,'' the statement said.   The guerrilla-controlled Afghan News Agency charged thatgovernment troops fire rockets at civilian targets to discredit themujahedeen, or Islamic holy warriors.   The rocket attacks came despite the cease-fire announced byPresident Najib to celebrate the three-day Eid al-Azha, or Feast ofSacrifice, which begins Thursday.   Najib's spokesman, Sarwar Yourish, told reporters that governmenttroops would lay down their weapons from midnight Tuesday untilmidnight Saturday to observe the festival. Eid al-Adha is thethree-day holiday marking the end of the annual Moslem hajj, orpilgrimage, to the holy cities of Mecca and Medina.   Hundreds of people marched in at least three rallies staged bythe governing People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan, calling formilitary action against Pakistan.   Najib's government has frequently accused Pakistan of directinvolvement in rocket attacks on Kabul, a charge that the governmentin Islamabad denies.   ``There is a growing resentment and anger among the Afghan peopleagainst Pakistan which is directly involved in the war against us,''Amanis said. ``The people of Afghanistan want the government to takeserious measures against Pakistan.''   He did not specify what measures might be taken. But diplomaticsources said the government was seeking the backing of publicopinion for a possible strike on rebel bases inside Pakistan.   Afghanistan and the Soviet Union have alleged that theguerrillas, along with Pakistani military advisers, are planning anoffensive on Kabul. Up until last week, guerrrilla efforts wereconcentrated on the city of Jalalabad.   The Soviet Union withdrew the last of its 115,000 troops on Feb.15 under a U.N.-mediated accord ending nine years of militaryinvolvement in Afghanistan. Moscow, however, has continued to supplyarms to the Kabul government.   In Moscow, the official Soviet news agency, Tass, said that``decisive retaliatory measures will be taken by Afghanistan'' inresponse to Pakistani support for the guerrillas.   ``In this case, responsibility for the consequences will rest onthe Pakistan military,'' Tass said.</TEXT></DOC>